</h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/10_339764c6-8830-4026-a54b-cda921d35a9b.png?v=1709033403" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/10_339764c6-8830-4026-a54b-cda921d35a9b.png?v=1709033403 1536w" width="1589" height="1059" alt="The Role of Leadership in Cultivating Distributed Intelligence - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="The Role of Leadership in Cultivating Distributed Intelligence - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-fbyfCU cCdixN pf-241_"/><p class="sc-hOGkXu hVdrsp pf-242_" tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Image by  sofiiashunkina via Envato Elements</p><p class="sc-hOGkXu hVdrsp pf-244_" tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Quantifying the impact of distributed intelligence can be tricky as its benefits are often indirect and long-term. However, businesses can look at metrics like the number of new ideas generated, the speed of problem resolution, or improvements in product innovation to gauge its effectiveness.
